# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: robotic-process-automation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:robotic-process-automation/business-process-automation] With the increasing adoption of artificial intelligence (AI), organizations are implementing AI-driven technologies that can process natural language, interpret unstructured datasets, and interact with users.
[src:robotic-process-automation/business-process-automation] These systems are designed to adapt to new types of problems with reduced reliance on human intervention.
[src:robotic-process-automation/business-process-automation] A business process management system differs from BPA.
[src:robotic-process-automation/business-process-automation] However, it is possible to implement automation based on a BPM implementation.
[src:robotic-process-automation/business-process-automation] The methods to achieve this vary, from writing custom application code to using specialist BPA tools.
[src:robotic-process-automation/business-process-automation] Robotic process automation (RPA) involves the deployment of attended or unattended software agents in an organization's environment.
[src:robotic-process-automation/business-process-automation] These software agents, or robots, are programmed to perform predefined structured and repetitive sets of business tasks or processes.
[src:robotic-process-automation/business-process-automation] Robotic process automation is designed to streamline workflows by delegating repetitive tasks to software agents, allowing human workers to focus on more complex and strategic activities.
[src:robotic-process-automation/business-process-automation] BPA providers typically focus on different industry sectors, but the underlying approach is generally similar in that they aim to provide the shortest route to automation by interacting with the user interface rather than modifying the application code or database behind it.
[src:robotic-process-automation/business-process-automation] Artificial intelligence software robots are used to handle unstructured data sets (like images, texts, audios) and are often deployed after implementing robotic process automation.
[src:robotic-process-automation/business-process-automation] They can, for instance, generate an automatic transcript from a video.
[src:robotic-process-automation/business-process-automation] The combination of automation and artificial intelligence (AI) enables autonomy for robots, along with the capability to perform cognitive tasks.
[src:robotic-process-automation/business-process-automation] At this stage, robots can learn and improve processes by analyzing and adapting them.
[src:robotic-process-automation/intelligent-automation] Intelligent automation applies the assembly line concept of breaking tasks into repetitive steps to improve business processes.
[src:robotic-process-automation/intelligent-automation] Rather than having humans perform each step, intelligent automation can replace steps with an intelligent software robot, improving efficiency.
[src:robotic-process-automation/intelligent-automation] Intelligent automation integrates robotic process automation (RPA) with artificial intelligence techniques (such as machine learning, natural-language processing, and computer vision) enabling systems to interpret data, make decisions, and adapt to changing inputs.
[src:robotic-process-automation/intelligent-automation] Modern platforms use a layered architecture combining workflow orchestration, low-code tools, integration middleware, and AI services to coordinate bots and data pipelines across organisational systems.
[src:robotic-process-automation/intelligent-automation] Intelligent automation is used to process unstructured content.
[src:robotic-process-automation/intelligent-automation] Common real-world applications include self-driving cars, self-checkouts at grocery stores, smart home assistants, and appliances.
[src:robotic-process-automation/intelligent-automation] Businesses can apply data and machine learning to build predictive analytics that react to consumer behavior changes, or to implement RPA to improve manufacturing floor operations.
[src:robotic-process-automation/intelligent-automation] For example, the technology has also been used to automate the workflow behind distributing COVID-19 vaccines.
[src:robotic-process-automation/intelligent-automation] Data provided by hospital systems’ electronic health records can be processed to identify and educate patients, and schedule vaccinations.
[src:robotic-process-automation/intelligent-automation] Intelligent automation can provide real-time insights on profitability and efficiency.
[src:robotic-process-automation/intelligent-automation] However, in an April 2022 survey by Alchemmy, despite three quarters of businesses acknowledging the importance of Artificial Intelligence to their future development, just a quarter of business leaders (25%) considered Intelligent Automation a “game changer” in understanding current performance.
[src:robotic-process-automation/intelligent-automation] 42% of CTOs see “shortage of talent” as the main obstacle to implementing Intelligent Automation in their business, while 36% of CEOs see ‘upskilling and professional development of existing workforce’ as the most significant adoption barrier.
[src:robotic-process-automation/intelligent-automation] IA is becoming increasingly accessible for firms of all sizes.
[src:robotic-process-automation/intelligent-automation] With this in mind, it is expected to continue to grow rapidly in all industries.
[src:robotic-process-automation/intelligent-automation] This technology has the potential to change the workforce.
[src:robotic-process-automation/intelligent-automation] As it advances, it will be able to perform increasingly complex and difficult tasks.
[src:robotic-process-automation/intelligent-automation] In addition, this may expose certain workforce issues as well as change how tasks are allocated.
[src:robotic-process-automation/intelligent-automation] Tools such as Semrush's *AI Visibility Toolkit* and *Enterprise AIO* reflect these developments by analysing how entities are referenced and represented within responses produced by large-language-model-based systems.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] OCR is a field of research in pattern recognition, artificial intelligence and computer vision.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] Early versions needed to be trained with images of each character, and worked on one font at a time.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] Advanced systems capable of producing a high degree of accuracy for most fonts are now common, and with support for a variety of image file format inputs.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] Some systems are capable of reproducing formatted output that closely approximates the original page including images, columns, and other non-textual components.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] Early optical character recognition may be traced to technologies involving telegraphy and creating reading devices for the blind.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] In 1914, Emanuel Goldberg developed a machine that read characters and converted them into standard telegraph code.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] Concurrently, Edmund Fournier d'Albe developed the Optophone, a handheld scanner that when moved across a printed page, produced tones that corresponded to specific letters or characters.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] In the late 1920s and into the 1930s, Emanuel Goldberg developed what he called a "Statistical Machine" for searching microfilm archives using an optical code recognition system.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] In 1931, he was granted US Patent number 1,838,389 for the invention.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] In 1974, Ray Kurzweil started the company Kurzweil Computer Products, Inc. and continued development of omni-font OCR, which could recognize text printed in virtually any font.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] (Kurzweil is often credited with inventing omni-font OCR, but it was in use by companies, including CompuScan, in the late 1960s and 1970s.) Kurzweil used the technology to create a reading machine for blind people to have a computer read text to them out loud.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] The device included a CCD-type flatbed scanner and a text-to-speech synthesizer.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] On January 13, 1976, the finished product was unveiled during a widely reported news conference headed by Kurzweil and the leaders of the National Federation of the Blind.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] In 1978, Kurzweil Computer Products began selling a commercial version of the optical character recognition computer program.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] LexisNexis was one of the first customers, and bought the program to upload legal paper and news documents onto its nascent online databases.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] Two years later, Kurzweil sold his company to Xerox, which eventually spun it off as Scansoft, which merged with Nuance Communications.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] In the 2000s, OCR was made available online as a service (WebOCR), in a cloud computing environment, and in mobile applications like real-time translation of foreign-language signs on a smartphone.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] With the advent of smartphones and smartglasses, OCR can be used in internet connected mobile device applications that extract text captured using the device's camera.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] These devices that do not have built-in OCR functionality will typically use an OCR API to extract the text from the image file captured by the device.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] The OCR API returns the extracted text, along with information about the location of the detected text in the original image back to the device app for further processing (such as text-to-speech) or display.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] Various commercial and open source OCR systems are available for most common writing systems, including Latin, Cyrillic, Arabic, Hebrew, Indic, Bengali (Bangla), Devanagari, Tamil, Chinese, Japanese, and Korean characters.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] OCR engines have been developed into software applications specializing in various subjects such as receipts, invoices, checks, and legal billing documents.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] OCR is generally an offline process, which analyses a static document.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] There are cloud based services which provide an online OCR API service.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] Handwriting movement analysis can be used as input to handwriting recognition.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] Instead of merely using the shapes of glyphs and words, this technique is able to capture motion, such as the order in which segments are drawn, the direction, and the pattern of putting the pen down and lifting it.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] This additional information can make the process more accurate.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] This technology is also known as "online character recognition", "dynamic character recognition", "real-time character recognition", and "intelligent character recognition".
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] OCR software often pre-processes images to improve the chances of successful recognition.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] Segmentation of fixed-pitch fonts is accomplished relatively simply by aligning the image to a uniform grid based on where vertical grid lines will least often intersect black areas.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] For proportional fonts, more sophisticated techniques are needed because whitespace between letters can sometimes be greater than that between words, and vertical lines can intersect more than one character.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] There are two basic types of core OCR algorithm, which may produce a ranked list of candidate characters.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] Software such as Cuneiform and Tesseract use a two-pass approach to character recognition.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] The second pass is known as adaptive recognition and uses the letter shapes recognized with high confidence on the first pass to better recognize the remaining letters on the second pass.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] This is advantageous for unusual fonts or low-quality scans where the font is distorted (e.g. blurred or faded).
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] Others like OCRopus and Tesseract use neural networks which are trained to recognize whole lines of text instead of focusing on single characters.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] A technique known as iterative OCR automatically crops a document into sections based on the page layout.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] OCR is then performed on each section individually using variable character confidence level thresholds to maximize page-level OCR accuracy.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] A patent from the United States Patent Office has been issued for this method.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] The OCR result can be stored in the standardized ALTO format, a dedicated XML schema maintained by the United States Library of Congress.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] Other common formats include hOCR and PAGE XML.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] For a list of optical character recognition software, see Comparison of optical character recognition software.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] OCR accuracy can be increased if the output is constrained by a lexicon – a list of words that are allowed to occur in a document.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] This might be, for example, all the words in the English language, or a more technical lexicon for a specific field.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] This technique can be problematic if the document contains words not in the lexicon, like proper nouns.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] Tesseract uses its dictionary to influence the character segmentation step, for improved accuracy.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] The output stream may be a plain text stream or file of characters, but more sophisticated OCR systems can preserve the original layout of the page and produce, for example, an annotated PDF that includes both the original image of the page and a searchable textual representation.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] Knowledge of the grammar of the language being scanned can also help determine if a word is likely to be a verb or a noun, for example, allowing greater accuracy.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] The Levenshtein Distance algorithm has also been used in OCR post-processing to further optimize results from an OCR API.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] In recent years, the major OCR technology providers began to tweak OCR systems to deal more efficiently with specific types of input.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] Beyond an application-specific lexicon, better performance may be had by taking into account business rules, standard expression, or rich information contained in color images.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] This strategy is called "Application-Oriented OCR" or "Customized OCR", and has been applied to OCR of license plates, invoices, screenshots, ID cards, driver's licenses, and automobile manufacturing.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] There are several techniques for solving the problem of character recognition by means other than improved OCR algorithms.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] Special fonts like OCR-A, OCR-B, or MICR fonts, with precisely specified sizing, spacing, and distinctive character shapes, allow a higher accuracy rate during transcription in bank check processing.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] Several prominent OCR engines were designed to capture text in popular fonts such as Arial or Times New Roman, and are incapable of capturing text in these fonts that are specialized and very different from popularly used fonts.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] As Google Tesseract can be trained to recognize new fonts, it can recognize OCR-A, OCR-B and MICR fonts.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] Palm OS used a special set of glyphs, known as Graffiti, which are similar to printed English characters but simplified or modified for easier recognition on the platform's computationally limited hardware.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] Users would need to learn how to write these special glyphs.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] Zone-based OCR restricts the image to a specific part of a document.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] This is often referred to as *Template OCR*.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] Crowdsourcing humans to perform the character recognition can quickly process images like computer-driven OCR, but with higher accuracy for recognizing images than that obtained via computers.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] Practical systems include the Amazon Mechanical Turk and reCAPTCHA.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] The National Library of Finland has developed an online interface for users to correct OCRed texts in the standardized ALTO format.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] Crowd sourcing has also been used not to perform character recognition directly but to invite software developers to develop image processing algorithms, for example, through the use of rank-order tournaments.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] Department of Energy (DOE), the Information Science Research Institute (ISRI) had the mission to foster the improvement of automated technologies for understanding machine printed documents, and it conducted the most authoritative of the *Annual Test of OCR Accuracy* from 1992 to 1996.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] Recognition of typewritten, Latin script text is still not 100% accurate even where clear imaging is available.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] One study based on recognition of 19th- and early 20th-century newspaper pages concluded that character-by-character OCR accuracy for commercial OCR software varied from 81% to 99%; total accuracy can be achieved by human review or Data Dictionary Authentication.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] Other areas – including recognition of hand printing, cursive handwriting, and printed text in other scripts (especially those East Asian language characters which have many strokes for a single character) – are still the subject of active research.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] The MNIST database is commonly used for testing systems' ability to recognize handwritten digits.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] Accuracy rates can be measured in several ways, and how they are measured can greatly affect the reported accuracy rate.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] For example, if word context (a lexicon of words) is not used to correct software finding non-existent words, a character error rate of 1% (99% accuracy) may result in an error rate of 5% or worse if the measurement is based on whether each whole word was recognized with no incorrect letters.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] Using a large enough dataset is important in a neural-network-based handwriting recognition solutions.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] On the other hand, producing natural datasets is very complicated and time-consuming.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] An example of the difficulties inherent in digitizing old text is the inability of OCR to differentiate between the "long s" and "f" characters.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] Recognition of cursive text has recognition rates even lower than that of hand-printed text.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] Higher rates of recognition of general cursive script will likely not be possible without the use of contextual or grammatical information.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] For example, recognizing entire words from a dictionary is easier than trying to parse individual characters from script.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] Reading the *Amount* line of a check (which is always a written-out number) is an example where using a smaller dictionary can increase recognition rates greatly.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] The shapes of individual cursive characters themselves simply do not contain enough information to accurately (greater than 98%) recognize all handwritten cursive script.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] Most programs allow users to set "confidence rates".
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] This means that if the software does not achieve their desired level of accuracy, a user can be notified for manual review.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] An error introduced by OCR scanning is sometimes termed a *scanno* (by analogy with the term *typo*).
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] Characters to support OCR were added to the Unicode Standard in June 1993, with the release of version 1.1.
[src:robotic-process-automation/optical-character-recognition] Some of these characters are mapped from fonts specific to MICR, OCR-A or OCR-B.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] In traditional workflow automation tools, a software developer produces a list of actions to automate a task and interface to the back end system using internal application programming interfaces (APIs) or dedicated scripting language.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] In contrast, RPA systems develop the action list by watching the user perform that task in the application's graphical user interface (GUI) and then perform the automation by repeating those tasks directly in the GUI.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] This can lower the barrier to the use of automation in products that might not otherwise feature APIs for this purpose.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] RPA tools have strong technical similarities to graphical user interface testing tools.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] These tools also automate interactions with the GUI, and often do so by repeating a set of demonstration actions performed by a user.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] RPA tools differ from such systems in that they allow data to be handled in and between multiple applications, for instance, receiving email containing an invoice, extracting the data, and then typing that into a bookkeeping system.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] As a form of automation, the concept has been around for a long time in the form of screen scraping, so long that to early PC users the reminder of it often blurs with the idea of malware infection.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] Yet compared to screen scraping, RPA is much more extensible, consisting of API integration into other enterprise applications, connectors into ITSM systems, terminal services and even some types of AI (e.g. machine learning) services such as image recognition.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] The hosting of RPA services also aligns with the metaphor of a software robot, with each robotic instance having its own virtual workstation, much like a human worker.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] The robot uses keyboard and mouse controls to take actions and execute automations.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] Normally, all of these actions take place in a virtual environment and not on screen; the robot does not need a physical screen to operate, rather it interprets the screen display electronically.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] The scalability of modern solutions based on architectures such as these owes much to the advent of virtualization technology, without which the scalability of large deployments would be limited by the available capacity to manage physical hardware and by the associated costs.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] The implementation of RPA in business enterprises has shown dramatic cost savings when compared to traditional non-RPA solutions.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] According to *Harvard Business Review*, most operations groups adopting RPA have promised their employees that automation would not result in layoffs.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] Instead, workers have been redeployed to do more interesting work.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] One academic study highlighted that knowledge workers did not feel threatened by automation: they embraced it and viewed the robots as team-mates.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] The same study highlighted that, rather than resulting in a lower "headcount", the technology was deployed in such a way as to achieve more work and greater productivity with the same number of people.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] Conversely, however, some analysts proffer that RPA represents a threat to the business process outsourcing (BPO) industry.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] The thesis behind this notion is that RPA will enable enterprises to "repatriate" processes from offshore locations into local data centers, with the benefit of this new technology.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] The effect, if true, will be to create high-value jobs for skilled process designers in onshore locations (and within the associated supply chain of IT hardware, data center management, etc.) but to decrease the available opportunity to low-skilled workers offshore.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] On the other hand, this discussion appears to be healthy ground for debate as another academic study was at pains to counter the so-called "myth" that RPA will bring back many jobs from offshore.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] Academic studies project that RPA, among other technological trends, is expected to drive a new wave of productivity and efficiency gains in the global labour market.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] Although not directly attributable to RPA alone, Oxford University conjectures that up to 35% of all jobs might be automated by 2035.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] There are geographic implications to the trend in robotic automation.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] On this basis, developed economies – with skills and technological infrastructure to develop and support a robotic automation capability – can be expected to achieve a net benefit from the trend.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] In a separate TEDx in 2019 talk, Japanese business executive, and former CIO of Barclays bank, Koichi Hasegawa noted that digital robots can be a positive effect on society if we start using a robot with empathy to help every person.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] He provides a case study of the Japanese insurance companies – Sompo Japan and Aioi – both of whom introduced bots to speed up the process of insurance pay-outs in past massive disaster incidents.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] It was also found in a 2021 study observing the effects of robotization in Europe that, the gender pay gap increased at a rate of .18% for every 1% increase in robotization of a given industry.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] Unassisted RPA, or **RPAAI**, is the next generation of RPA related technologies.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] Technological advancements around artificial intelligence allow a process to be run on a computer without needing input from a user.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] Hyperautomation is the application of advanced technologies like RPA, artificial intelligence, machine learning (ML) and process mining to augment workers and automate processes in ways that are significantly more impactful than traditional automation capabilities.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] Hyperautomation is the combination of technologies that allow faster application authorship (like low-code and no-code) with automation technologies that coordinate different worker types (i.e. human and artificial) for intelligent and strategic workflow optimization.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] Gartner's report notes that this trend was kicked off with robotic process automation (RPA).
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] The report notes that, "RPA alone is not hyperautomation.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] Back office clerical processes outsourced by large organisations - particularly those sent offshore - tend to be simple and transactional in nature, requiring little (if any) analysis or subjective judgement.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] This would seem to make an ideal starting point for organizations beginning to adopt robotic automation for the back office.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] Conversely however, a BPO provider may seek to effect some form of client lock-in by means of automation.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] This effect occurs as the associated cost savings made through automation would - temporarily at least - have to be reintroduced to the business whilst the technical solution is reimplemented in the new operational context.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] The geographically agnostic nature of software means that new business opportunities may arise for those organisations that have a political or regulatory impediment to offshoring or outsourcing.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] A robotised automation can be hosted in a data centre in any jurisdiction and this has two major consequences for BPO providers.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] Firstly, for example, a sovereign government may not be willing or legally able to outsource the processing of tax affairs and security administration.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] On this basis, if robots are compared to a human workforce, this creates a genuinely new opportunity for a "third sourcing" option, after the choices of onshore vs. offshore.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] Secondly, and conversely, BPO providers have previously relocated outsourced operations to different political and geographic territories in response to changing wage inflation and new labour arbitrage opportunities elsewhere.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] By contrast, a data centre solution would seem to offer a fixed and predictable cost base that, if sufficiently low in cost on a robot vs. human basis, would seem to eliminate any potential need or desire to continually relocate operational bases.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] The typical benefits of robotic automation include reduced cost; increased speed, accuracy, and consistency; improved quality and scalability of production.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] Automation can also provide extra security, especially for sensitive data and financial services.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] While robotic process automation has many benefits including cost efficiency and consistency in performance, it also has some limitations.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] Current RPA solutions demand continual technical support to handle system changes, therefore it lacks the ability to autonomously adapt to new conditions.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] Because of this limitation, the system sometimes needs manual reconfiguration, which in turn has an effect on efficiency.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] A principal barrier to the adoption of self-service is often technological: it may not always be feasible or economically viable to retrofit new interfaces onto existing systems.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] Moreover, organisations may wish to layer a variable and configurable set of process rules on top of the system interfaces which may vary according to market offerings and the type of customer.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] This only adds to the cost and complexity of the technological implementation.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] Robotic automation software provides a pragmatic means of deploying new services in this situation, where the robots simply mimic the behaviour of humans to perform the back-end transcription or processing.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] The relative affordability of this approach arises from the fact that no new IT transformation or investment is required; instead the software robots simply leverage greater use out of existing IT assets.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] There are however several risks with RPA.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] Criticism includes risks of stifling innovation and creating a more complex maintenance environment of existing software that now needs to consider the use of graphical user interfaces in a way they weren't intended to be used.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] RPA is based on automation technology following a predefined workflow, and artificial intelligence is data-driven and focuses on processing information to make predictions.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] Therefore, there is a distinct difference between how the two systems operate.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] AI aims to mimic human intelligence, whereas RPA is focused on reproducing tasks that are typically human-directed.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] Moreover, RPA could also be explained as virtual robots that take over routinized human work, it can identify data by interpreting the underlying tags.
[src:robotic-process-automation/robotic-process-automation] RPA, therefore, is based on machine learning, whereas AI utilizes self-learning technologies.
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] Normally, data transfer between programs is accomplished using data structures suited for automated processing by computers, not people.
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] Such interchange formats and protocols are typically rigidly structured, well-documented, easily parsed, and minimize ambiguity.
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] Very often, these transmissions are not human-readable at all.
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] Thus, the key element that distinguishes data scraping from regular parsing is that the data being consumed is intended for display to an end-user, rather than as an input to another program.
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] It is therefore usually neither documented nor structured for convenient parsing.
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] Data scraping often involves ignoring binary data (usually images or multimedia data), display formatting, redundant labels, superfluous commentary, and other information which is either irrelevant or hinders automated processing.
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] Data scraping is most often done either to interface to a legacy system, which has no other mechanism which is compatible with current hardware, or to interface to a third-party system which does not provide a more convenient API.
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] In the second case, the operator of the third-party system will often see screen scraping as unwanted, due to reasons such as increased system load, the loss of advertisement revenue, or the loss of control of the information content.
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] Data scraping is generally considered an *ad hoc*, inelegant technique, often used only as a "last resort" when no other mechanism for data interchange is available.
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] Aside from the higher programming and processing overhead, output displays intended for human consumption often change structure frequently.
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] Humans can cope with this easily, but a computer program will fail.
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] Depending on the quality and the extent of error handling logic present in the computer, this failure can result in error messages, corrupted output or even program crashes.
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] However, setting up a data scraping pipeline nowadays is straightforward, requiring minimal programming effort to meet practical needs (especially in biomedical data integration).
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] Although the use of physical "dumb terminal" IBM 3270s is slowly diminishing, as more and more mainframe applications acquire Web interfaces, some Web applications merely continue to use the technique of **screen scraping** to capture old screens and transfer the data to modern front-ends.
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] Screen scraping is normally associated with the programmatic collection of visual data from a source, instead of parsing data as in web scraping.
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] Originally, *screen scraping* referred to the practice of reading text data from a computer display terminal's screen.
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] This was generally done by reading the terminal's memory through its auxiliary port, or by connecting the terminal output port of one computer system to an input port on another.
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] The term screen scraping is also commonly used to refer to the bidirectional exchange of data.
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] This could be the simple cases where the controlling program navigates through the user interface, or more complex scenarios where the controlling program is entering data into an interface meant to be used by a human.
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] As a concrete example of a classic screen scraper, consider a hypothetical legacy system dating from the 1960s—the dawn of computerized data processing.
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] Computer to user interfaces from that era were often simply text-based dumb terminals which were not much more than virtual teleprinters (such systems are still in use today, for various reasons).
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] The desire to interface such a system to more modern systems is common.
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] A robust solution will often require things no longer available, such as source code, system documentation, APIs, or programmers with experience in a 50-year-old computer system.
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] In such cases, the only feasible solution may be to write a screen scraper that "pretends" to be a user at a terminal.
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] The screen scraper might connect to the legacy system via Telnet, emulate the keystrokes needed to navigate the old user interface, process the resulting display output, extract the desired data, and pass it on to the modern system.
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] In the 1980s, financial data providers such as Reuters, Telerate, and Quotron displayed data in 24×80 format intended for a human reader.
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] Users of this data, particularly investment banks, wrote applications to capture and convert this character data as numeric data for inclusion into calculations for trading decisions without re-keying the data.
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] The common term for this practice, especially in the United Kingdom, was *page shredding*, since the results could be imagined to have passed through a paper shredder.
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] Internally Reuters used the term 'logicized' for this conversion process, running a sophisticated computer system on VAX/VMS called the Logicizer.
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] More modern screen scraping techniques include capturing the bitmap data from the screen and running it through an OCR engine, or for some specialised automated testing systems, matching the screen's bitmap data against expected results.
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] This can be combined in the case of GUI applications, with querying the graphical controls by programmatically obtaining references to their underlying programming objects.
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] A sequence of screens is automatically captured and converted into a database.
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] Another modern adaptation to these techniques is to use, instead of a sequence of screens as input, a set of images or PDF files, so there are some overlaps with generic "document scraping" and report mining techniques.
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] There are many tools that can be used for screen scraping.
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] Web pages are built using text-based mark-up languages (HTML and XHTML), and frequently contain a wealth of useful data in text form.
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] However, most web pages are designed for human end-users and not for ease of automated use.
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] Because of this, tool kits that scrape web content were created.
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] A web scraper is an API or tool to extract data from a website.
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] Companies like Amazon AWS and Google provide **web scraping** tools, services, and public data available free of cost to end-users.
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] Newer forms of web scraping involve listening to data feeds from web servers.
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] For example, JSON is commonly used as a transport storage mechanism between the client and the web server.
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] A web scraper uses a website's URL to extract data, and stores this data for subsequent analysis.
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] This method of web scraping enables the extraction of data in an efficient and accurate manner.
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] Recently, companies have developed web scraping systems that rely on using techniques in DOM parsing, computer vision and natural language processing to simulate the human processing that occurs when viewing a webpage to automatically extract useful information.
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] Large websites usually use defensive algorithms to protect their data from web scrapers and to limit the number of requests an IP or IP network may send.
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] This has caused an ongoing battle between website developers and scraping developers.
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] The legality and ethics of data scraping are often argued.
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] Scraping publicly accessible data is generally legal, however scraping in a manner that infringes a website's terms of service, breaches security measures, or invades user privacy can lead to legal action.
[src:robotic-process-automation/screen-scraping] Moreover, some websites particularly prohibit data scraping in their robots.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] From a more abstract perspective, workflow may be considered a view or representation of real work.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] The flow being described may refer to a document, service, or product that is being transferred from one step to another.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] Workflows may be viewed as fundamental building blocks to be combined with other parts of an organization's structure, such as information technology, teams, projects, and hierarchies.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] The development of the workflow concept occurred across several loosely defined, overlapping eras.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] The modern history of workflows can be traced to Frederick Taylor and Henry Gantt, although the term "workflow" was not used in this context during their lifetimes.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] One of the earliest instances of the term "work flow" was in a railway engineering journal from 1921.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] Taylor and Gantt launched the study of the deliberate, rational organization of work, primarily in the context of manufacturing.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] This gave rise to time and motion studies.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] Related concepts include job shops and queuing systems (Markov chains).
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] The 1948 book *Cheaper by the Dozen* introduced the emerging workflow concept to the context of family life.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] The invention of the typewriter and the copier helped spread the study of the rational organization of labor from the manufacturing shop floor to the office.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] Filing and other sophisticated systems for managing physical information flows evolved.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] Several events likely contributed to the development of formalized information workflows.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] First, the field of optimization theory matured and developed mathematical optimization techniques.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] For example, Soviet mathematician and economist Leonid Kantorovich developed the seeds of linear programming in 1939 through efforts to solve a plywood manufacturer's production optimization issues.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] Second, World War II and the Apollo program drove process improvement forward with their demands for the rational organization of work.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] Juran led to a focus on quality, first in Japanese companies, and more globally from the 1980s.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] There were various movements ranging from total quality management to Six Sigma, and then more qualitative notions of business process re-engineering.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] This led to more efforts to improve workflows in both knowledge economy sectors and manufacturing.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] Thought leaders recognized variable demands on workflows when they considered the theory of critical paths and moving bottlenecks.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] Basu and Kumar noted that the term "workflow management" referred to tasks associated with the flow of information through the value chain rather than the flow of material goods: they characterise the definition, analysis and management of information as "workflow management".
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] The transmission of information from one organization to another is a critical issue in this inter-organizational context and raises the importance of tasks they describe as "validation", "verification" and "data usage analysis".
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] A workflow management system (WfMS) is a software system for creating, executing, and monitoring a defined sequence of processes and tasks, with the broad goals of increasing productivity, reducing costs, becoming more agile, and improving information exchange within an organization.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] These systems may be process-centric or data-centric, and they may also represent the workflow as graphical maps.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] A workflow management system may also include an extensible interface so that external software applications can be integrated, providing support for wide area workflows that provide both faster response times and improved productivity.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] The workflow concept is closely related to several fields in operations research and other areas that study the nature of work either quantitatively or qualitatively, such as artificial intelligence (in particular, the sub-discipline of AI planning) and ethnography.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] The term "workflow" is more commonly used in particular industries like printing, as well as professional domains such as clinical laboratories.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] It may have particular specialized meanings in these areas.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] **Planning and scheduling**: A plan is a description of the logically necessary, partially ordered set of activities required to accomplish a specific goal given certain starting conditions.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] A plan, when augmented with a schedule and resource allocation calculations, completely defines a particular *instance* of systematic processing in pursuit of a goal.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] A workflow may be viewed as an often optimal or near-optimal realization of the mechanisms required to execute the same plan repeatedly.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] **Flow control**: This is a control concept applied to workflows, to distinguish from static control of buffers of material or orders, to mean a more dynamic control of flow speed and flow volumes in motion and in process.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] Such orientation to dynamic aspects is the basic foundation to prepare for more advanced job shop controls, such as just-in-time or just-in-sequence.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] **In-transit visibility**: This monitoring concept applies to transported material as well as to work in process or work in progress, i.e., workflows.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] Insurance claims processing is an example of an information-intensive, document-driven workflow.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] Wikipedia editing can be modeled as a stochastic workflow.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] The Getting Things Done system is a model of personal workflow management for information workers.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] In software development, support and other industries, the concept of *follow-the-sun* describes a process of passing unfinished work across time zones.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] In scientific experiments, the overall process (tasks and data flow) can be described as a directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] This DAG is referred to as a workflow, e.g., Brain Imaging workflows.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] In healthcare data analysis, a workflow can be identified or used to represent a sequence of steps that comprise a complex data analysis.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] In service-oriented architectures, an application can be represented through an executable workflow, where different, possibly geographically distributed, service components interact to provide the corresponding functionality under the control of a workflow management system.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] In shared services, an application can be in the practice of developing robotic process automation (called RPA or RPAAI for self-guided RPA 2.0 based on artificial intelligence) which results in the deployment of attended or unattended software agents to an organization's environment.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] These software agents, or robots, are deployed to perform pre-defined structured and repetitive sets of business tasks or processes.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] Artificial intelligence software robots are deployed to handle unstructured data sets and are deployed after performing and deploying robotic process automation.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] Measurement: Many of the concepts used to measure scheduling systems in operations research are useful for measuring general workflows.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] These include throughput, processing time, and other regular metrics.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] Specialized connotations: The term "workflow" has specialized connotations in information technology, document management, and imaging.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] Since 1993, one trade consortium specifically focused on workflow management and the interoperability of workflow management systems, the Workflow Management Coalition.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] Scientific workflow systems: These found wide acceptance in the fields of bioinformatics and cheminformatics in the early 2000s, when they met the need for multiple interconnected tools that handle multiple data formats and large data quantities.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] Also, the paradigm of scientific workflows resembles the well-established practice of Perl programming in life science research organizations, making this adoption a natural step towards more structured infrastructure setup.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] Human-machine interaction: Several conceptualizations of mixed-initiative workflows have been studied, particularly in the military, where automated agents play roles just as humans do.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] For innovative, adaptive, and collaborative human work, the techniques of human interaction management are required.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] Workflow analysis: Workflow systems allow users to develop executable processes with no familiarity with formal programming concepts.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] Automated workflow analysis techniques can help users analyze the properties of user workflows to conduct verification of certain properties before executing them, e.g., analyzing flow control or data flow.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] Examples of tools based on formal analysis frameworks have been developed and used for the analysis of scientific workflows and can be extended to the analysis of other types of workflows.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] Several workflow improvement theories have been proposed and implemented in the modern workplace.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] Resource evaluation (both physical and human) is essential to evaluating hand-off points and creating smoother transitions between tasks.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] A workflow can usually be described using formal or informal flow diagramming techniques and displays directed flows between processing steps.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] Components can only be plugged together if the output of one previous (set of) component(s) is equal to the mandatory input requirements of the following component(s).
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] Thus, the essential description of a component actually comprises only input and output that are described fully in terms of data types and their meaning (semantics).
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] The algorithms' or rules' descriptions need only be included when there are several alternative ways to transform one type of input into one type of output – possibly with different accuracy, speed, etc.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] When the components are non-local services that are invoked remotely via a computer network, such as Web services, developers must consider additional descriptors (such as QoS and availability).
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] A workflow application is a software application that automates a process or processes to some degree.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] These processes are usually business-related but can be any process that requires a series of steps to be automated via software.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] Some process steps may require human intervention, such as development and approval of custom text, but functions that can be automated should be handled by the application.
[src:robotic-process-automation/workflow-automation] Advanced applications allow users to introduce new components into the operation.
